// SNAC 44kHz codebook lookup, real-time variant: identical math to
// ncs.snac_44kh.embedcodes (same decode_codes.onnx graph -- the codebook
// lookup + Tile-based per-level upsample is pointwise per output frame,
// no temporal receptive field, so it's exactly as correct running
// continuously on small rt~ blocks as on a whole buffer~). The codes
// INPUT is a plain "list" per level (tiny regardless of rate), but the
// embeddings OUTPUT is chunked via the buffer modules' messageix/tensor
// protocol -- see kMaxChunkAtoms' comment below for why 32k/44k's much
// larger block needs this where snac_24kh's rt~ embedcodes didn't.
// Identical network to snac_32kh (only sampling rate and weights
// differ) -- see ncs.rt.snac_24kh.embedcodes.cpp for the full design
// rationale this module mirrors.
//
// UNLIKE the buffer module, this is a continuous stream feeding
// ncs.rt.snac_44kh.decode~'s running context -- every block must be
// looked up in order, none can be dropped. So (like ncs.rt.snac_44kh.vq)
// the worker loop below does NOT collapse to "only the latest" the way
// every buffer-mode module does, and there's no CancellableRun: a
// mid-stream Run() is never stale.
static constexpr int kNumLevels = 4;

// Real-time duration one block represents -- matches
// ncs.rt.snac_44kh.encode_tilde.cpp's kBlockSize(12288)/kModelSampleRate(44100);
// this module doesn't otherwise need those constants, only their ratio,
// as the divisor for @monitor_rtf's real-time factor (see
// PerformanceMonitorScope in shared_external_helpers.h).
static constexpr double kBlockDurationMs = 12288.0 / 44100.0 * 1000.0;

// Each output (sum + 4 per-level embeddings) is kLatentDim(1024) x T
// floats -- for a T_block of 32 that's 32768 atoms, well past the
// single-list-message crash threshold documented in
// ncs.snac_24kh.encode.cpp (~15k-20k atoms confirmed to crash Max's own
// outlet_cache/real_outlet_list via a raw memmove overflow). Unlike
// snac_24kh's rt~ embedcodes (768*T atoms, small enough for a plain
// list), these outlets send the buffer modules' messageix/tensor
// chunked protocol instead. The codes INPUT stays a plain "list" --
// codes are tiny (at most T_block ints per level) regardless of rate.
//
// kMaxChunkAtoms is 12000 here (vs the buffer modules' 4000) -- see
// ncs.rt.snac_44kh.encode_tilde.cpp's kMaxChunkAtoms comment: this is a
// continuous real-time stream, and flush_output()'s one-message-per-10ms
// pacing means fewer, bigger chunks matter for keeping up with the
// model's block cadence instead of starving decode~'s ring buffer.
static constexpr size_t kMaxChunkAtoms = 12000;

// flush_output() drains up to this many queued messages per 10ms tick
// (see its comment) instead of exactly one -- see
// ncs.rt.snac_44kh.encode_tilde.cpp's kMaxSendsPerTick comment for the
// full rationale (same fix, same hop-cost problem, same conservative cap
// given this is a chunked-payload code path).
static constexpr int kMaxSendsPerTick = 4;

struct EmbedRequest {
    std::vector<int64_t> codes[kNumLevels];
    double scale[kNumLevels];
};

